[26:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually quite interesting. So I played around with this a bit and the default shift value of this workflow is three. If you lower the shift value to something like one, then the contrast and the detail seems to be a lot higher.'

[27:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Whereas if you set the shift value to something like six, then it seems to be softer with less detail. But feel free to play around with this shift value yourself and see how it affects your image. And then finally, your prompt and'

[27:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the resolution will be plugged into here to generate the image. So here we have the number of steps it takes to generate the image. The more steps you have, the longer it will take, but the higher quality it will be. And vice versa. It'

[27:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'seems like the sweet spot is 8 to 10 steps. But again, feel free to play around with it. If you set the step count to like four to six, it does generate faster and the image tends to be softer in details with more noise. If'

[27:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you increase the step count to something above 10, then it can slightly improve sharpness, but sometimes it makes it too sharp. And then for CFG, this is basically how literally you want the AI'

[27:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to follow your prompt. Now, Zimage Turbo is specifically designed to work within the range of a CFG of 1. Whereas for stable diffusion, you can often set the CFG to something super high like six or'

[28:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even 10. Notice that for Z image edit, often if you go above three, then it\'s already going to mess up your image. Now, the CFG is basically how literally the AI should follow your prompt. So, if you want to generate a lot of text in'

[28:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your image and you want to make sure it gets the text 100% correct, then you can try to increase the CFG slightly to like 1 point something or two. Also, if you increase the CFG, it tends to saturate'

[28:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the colors a bit. And then if you want like some softer or less saturated images, then sometimes a lower CFG of like.5 to one can actually give you that result. Again, feel free to play around with this until you find the optimum'

[28:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'combination for your use case. Also, you might have noticed that here there\'s not really any negative prompt, and that\'s because with a cfg of one, it basically ignores your negative prompt. And then'

[28:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'next, we have sampler name anduler. This is basically the algorithm that\'s used to generate the image. Now, the default one that they have here is already pretty good, so I just tend to leave it at this. However, if you want to'

[29:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
